President Biden spoke at the Scottish Event Campus in Glasgow, Scotland, during the COP26 climate conference. He highlighted the importance of the United States' presence at COP26 and its commitment to addressing the climate crisis. He thanked the United Kingdom and Prime Minister Boris Johnson for hosting the conference and praised Prince Charles for his efforts to engage the private sector in climate action. President Biden emphasized the need for decisive action in the next decade to limit global warming to 1.5 degrees Celsius and expressed support for the agreement by over 100 countries to halt and reverse deforestation by 2030. He reaffirmed the United States' goal of reducing emissions by 50-52% by 2030 and outlined initiatives to address methane emissions, promote climate-smart agriculture, drive innovation, and invest in clean infrastructure. He also mentioned the President's Emergency Plan for Adaptation and Resilience (PREPARE) and the long-term strategy to achieve net-zero emissions by 2050. President Biden addressed concerns about U.S.-China relations and emphasized the need for competition rather than conflict, while urging China to play by the rules. He expressed confidence in passing his Build Back Better plan and dismissed concerns about inflation, attributing price increases to COVID-related supply chain disruptions. President Biden also commented on the Virginia and New Jersey elections, expressing optimism about the Democratic Party's chances of winning. He acknowledged the frustration of climate activists but highlighted the progress made at COP26 and the growing awareness of the climate crisis among the general public. He emphasized the need for continued action and the involvement of the private sector in addressing climate change.